And that sets the stage for our final scene.

How realistic was this hack? The depicted steps are all authentic; as usual, I ensured everything could be reproduced end-to-end in a virtual machine using the same tools. But we did take artistic liberties to shorten the time required to crack a LUKS partition, especially given how slow the algorithm is. Elliotâ€™s knowledge and approach maximized his odds, but he still got lucky. It might have taken days or weeks to crack Romeroâ€™s password with an extensive wordlist. In any case, that detail doesnâ€™t fundamentally change how the rest of the episode plays out.
Determining the fate of five/nine

â€œI transferred the keys from the arcade to a remote virtual machine on our box at home. I then burned it to a CD. Youâ€™ll find the seed data and the algorithm embedded in one of those pictures. Youâ€™ll know the one.â€â€Šâ€”â€ŠMr. Robot

Elliot returns to his computer and loads the CD full of pictures of him and his father, as we originally saw in season one. I imagined that heâ€™d use a mix of intuition and technical analysis to find the right file. We see him examine several images using a Python script, lsb.py, that performs statistical analysis to search for evidence of steganographyâ€Šâ€”â€Šof hidden data otherwise invisible to the naked eye. This particular tool focuses on a common technique whereby the least-significant bit (LSB) of pixel values is used to store other data.
Analyzing and extracting hidden data from one of the image files

Elliot is convinced that he has found the right image: him and his father dressed as Marty and Doc Brown.

He reviews a hex dump of the first 256 bytes of the file with the command:

